75\margtsxn1440\margbsxn360\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li7402\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-965\slmult0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 9}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-965\slmult0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 does the formulation of the test by Potgieter, J.A., what the test actually involves, viz. that the Court will not interfere with a ruling made by the taxing master in every case where its view of the matter in dispute, differs from that of the taxing master., but only when it is satisfied that the taxing master's view of the matter differs so materially from its own that it should be held to vitiate his ruling.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li14\fi2225\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-965\slmult0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 I turn now to applicants' attack on the taxing master's ruling in respect of the various items mentioned above,}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5573\fi0\ri0\sb907\sa0\tldot\tx7632 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 Items/{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn3219\margrsxn814\margtsxn1397\margbsxn360\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li2261\fi5011\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-972\slmult0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 10 \ul Items 21 and 22\ul0  : \ul Heads of argument}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi2225\ri0\sb245\sa0\sl-965\slmult0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 The applicants contend that the taxing master should have allowed separate fees for the drawing of heads of argument and that he erred in allowing a composite fee relating to the whole of the appeal, as mentioned above. It appears from the taxing master's report that it has always been the practice of the taxing master of this Court to determine a composite fee for the whole of an appeal, and to make allowance for the drawing of heads of argument when determining that fee. The applicants accept this to have been the case up *}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5875\fi0\ri0\sb936\sa0\tldot\tx7474 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 to/{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn3265\margrsxn421\margtsxn1440\margbsxn720\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li7236\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw-10\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 11}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi0\ri0\sb130\sa0\sl-972\slmult0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 to now, but they submit that the recent amendment to Rule 8(1) has made it necessary to alter this practice. In terms of this amendment, introduced by GN R248 of 8 February 1980, parties to an appeal may be required, if so decided by the Chief Justice, to lodge their heads of argument with the registrar of the Court before a date has been allocated for the hearing of the appeal, and the applicants' contention is that where heads of argument are called for at such an early stage, "the successful party will only receive his full indemnity if a separate fee is allowed for heads of argument." (The quotation}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li6314\fi0\ri0\sb1015\sa0\tldot\tx7632 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 is/{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn3175\margrsxn360\margtsxn1440\margbsxn360\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li7402\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-965\slmult0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw-6\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 12}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-965\slmult0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 is from counsel's heads of argument.) It is sub\-mitted that when counsel is required to draw heads of argument well before the appeal (as happened in the present case), he will have to work up the appeal again before he appears in Court. Consequently, it is said, a separate fee should be allowed for the drawing of heads of argument. The submission has no real substance. Heads of argument are drawn when counsel has done his research and prepared for the appeal. They reflect the result of that research and preparation, and if counsel should thereafter, due to the lapse of time, regard it as}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li4651\fi0\ri0\sb929\sa0\tldot\tx7632 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 necessary/{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn3201\margrsxn573\margtsxn1040\margbsxn360\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi7258\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-965\slmult0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 13 necessary to consider them again, the extra work involved will normally not be so substantial as to warrant a separate fee. A taxing master could, of course, depending on the circumstances, and if persuaded that the extra work was such as to warrant his doing so, make allowance for that work when determining a composite fee for the whole of the appeal. I may add in this connection that the taxing master states in his report that, in considering the question of counsel's fees, he had regard \ul inter alia\ul0  to "die feit dat argumentshoofde elf maande voor die verhoor van die app\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\f2\cchs0 \'e8\hich\af0\dbch\af2\loch\f0\cchs0 l aangevra is." The applicants were asked on 24 June 1981 to lodge their}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5429\fi0\ri0\sb936\sa0\tldot\tx7646 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 heads/....{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn3265\margrsxn385\margtsxn1440\margbsxn360\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li7\fi7114\ri374\sb0\sa0\sl-965\slmult0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw-6\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 14 \expndtw0 heads of argument with the registrar by 24 October}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi0\ri749\sb0\sa0\sl-965\slmult0\tx1202 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 1981.{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }In a letter dated 2 November 1981 their\line attorneys requested the Chief Justice to allocate}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-965\slmult0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 a date for the hearing of the appeal on which counsel for all the parties would be available, and they stated that counsel would be available during the weeks commencing 13 September 1982 or 20 September}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-965\slmult0\tx1202 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 1982.{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }The appeal was set down for 13 September\line 1982. (On 3 June 1982, I may add, the applicants'\line attorneys addressed a letter to the registrar in\line which they inquired about the possibility of postponing\line the appeal, for the convenience of counsel, to the}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5868\fi0\ri0\sb914\sa0\tldot\tx8258 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 November/{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn3132\margrsxn821\margtsxn1440\margbsxn360\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi7243\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-965\slmult0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 15 November term of 1982). In these circumstances it is difficult to see how the lengthy lapse of time between the drawing of the heads of argument and the date of the hearing of the appeal can be advanced as a reason why the taxing master should have allowed counsel a separate fee for drawing the heads of argument.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li7\fi2225\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-965\slmult0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 Counsel for the applicants made a few further submissions in support of his contention that a practice should be adopted of allowing a separate fee for the drawing of heads of argument. He submitted, firstly, that it may happen, if heads}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li6199\fi0\ri0\sb943\sa0\tldot\tx7654 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 of/{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn3280\margrsxn421\margtsxn1440\margbsxn360\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li7\fi7193\ri749\sb0\sa0\sl-965\slmult0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw-12\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 16 \expndtw0 of argument are to be lodged with the registrar}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi137\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-965\slmult0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 before a date has been allocated for the hearing of the appeal, that counsel who drew the heads may not be available to argue the appeal, in which event he will receive no fee for the appeal itself. 1 realise that such a situation may arise, but such a possibility can hardly provide justification for the adoption of a practice as suggested by counsel. The burden of the party who loses an appeal ought not to be increased because counsel for the successful party, who drew the heads of argument, could not make himself available for arguing}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5688\fi0\ri0\sb922\sa0\tldot\tx7279 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 the/{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn3244\margrsxn536\margtsxn1440\margbsxn360\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li7\fi7394\ri403\sb0\sa0\sl-965\slmult0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw-2\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 17 \expndtw0 the appeal. It should be observed, also, that counsel's submission has no real relevance to the facts of the present case, for counsel who drew the heads of argument also argued the appeal.}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi2225\ri0\sb7\sa0\sl-965\slmult0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 Counsel also submitted that a separate fee should be allowed for drawing heads of argument because they are documents of "fundamental importance" which are required by the rules of Court and which are intended to assist the parties to the appeal}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li14\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-972\slmult0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 and the Court. Heads of argument which are required by the rules of Court, counsel submitted, referring to the case of \ul Minister of Water Affairs v. Meyburg\ul0 ,}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li5587\fi0\ri0\sb806\sa0\tldot\tx7495 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs22 1966/{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \sect\sectd \sbkpage\pgwsxn11909\pghsxn16834\marglsxn3330\margrsxn529\margtsxn1116\margbsxn360\cols1\colsx60 \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li0\fi7171\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-965\slmult0 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs24 18 1966(4) 5.A. 51 (E C D) at p. 52 H, should be distinguished from "so-called heads of argument" which are not required by the rules of Court, but are prepared by counsel for the convenience of himself and the Court and are handed to his opponent merely as a matter of courtesy. Counsel's submission is that while the costs of drawing heads of argument of the latter kind are not allowed to counsel in a party and party bill costs, they should be allowed when heads of argument are required by the rules of Court, and that the \ul dictum\ul0  to the contrary of Galgut, J., in \ul City Deep Ltd. v. Johannesburg City Council\ul0 , 1973(2) S.A. 109 (W.) at p. 115 \ul i.f\ul0 . was}\par \pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li4630\fi0\ri0\sb792\sa0\tldot\tx7106 \f2\fs20{\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\fs24 obiter/{\charscalex100\expndtw0\tab }}\par \se